In the harmonic oscillator model, the vibrational frequency scales as \(
u \propto \sqrt{k/\mu}\), hence the wavenumber \(	ilde{
u}=
u/c\) also scales as \(1/\sqrt{\mu}\) for fixed \(k\). Increasing \(\mu\) therefore lowers \(	ilde{
u}\), which is the isotope shift used to interpret vibrational spectra. The “unchanged” option ignores reduced mass, and “increase” corresponds to incorrectly placing \(\mu\) in the numerator.
